This is a frame vertex for Mendel / Prusa Mendel using less material than the solid version. I know there are other attempts of vertexes - so this is just an additional one. There is a version with feet and one without.

The vertex without feet weights 12 grams.
I printed it in ABS with 4 shells, 0.35mm nozzle, and with relatively coarse infill (you can see the infill on the picture of the vertexes while printing).
If I calculate that weight back to filament length it tells me that it takes about 1650mm of 3mm feedstock to print one of these. Comments after the second print:
Printed the version with feet now.
Again in ABS, this time with 2 shells, 0.35mm nozzle, same coarse infill and they are 11 grams. They feel really robust but I did not screw a frame together yet so still needs to be tested if two such thin shells are ok.

With LED lights and a fan for ABS, my printer needed several switches for +12 DC supplies.  In case of problems, I also wanted a DC switch to turn off the RAMPS board, just in case.    
Switches from RS or local auto store have LED light inside (red, blue, white or green are available) and rated for 10 amp load.

With all the stuff mounted inside the rails, the wire connections needed to be between the rails and that kept me from using a flat plate style.  
Using LED lighted switches from RS or your local auto store, this bathtub configuration prints with default support.    I used 0.18 honeycomb fill.   Versions for 2 mounting holes and 4 mounting holes are included.   2 are plenty, of course!  
Mount the switches and tighten the nuts with long nose pliers.  Ground and +12 VDC can be strapped together for all switches.  Use the LEDs to check polarity.  If they light with the switch 'on', your wiring is correct.   The long center contact goes to your load, with a 1/4" push-on connection to each load.  
There is minimal gap between switches, but if the body turns after you mount everything, just put a small drop of CA instant set glue at the top of the gap between switch body and the printed plastic plate.

So my mum broke her Opel Agila key. looking inside I could not refrain from designing her a new (and better!) cover for her key!
Here is the result of my work if you need it! Just dismount the old car key, take the three components inside (the key, the RFID for immobilizer and the round radio controller), place them in your just printed cover and close it with two little screws. Unfortunately I can't tell you what screw you need because I've taken two that I had at office but they are fairly common. You need the same thread as the original key as the inside hole of the key's hole is threaded.

Assembling

At this point place the upper cover on the bottom cover and press it down firmly while you screw in the bottom screw (the one that will go inside the key's hole).
then you can insert the upper screw.

title: Craftbot Plus Digital Dial micrometer mount

description.text:
Nice digital calibration to calibrate your Craft Plus printerbed.
You can use just one calibration tool, but it's also possible to use 2 at the same time.

The digital micrometer: a Highly accurate digital shockproof dial indicator. Range 0-12,7mm / 0.5", 0.01 millimeter scale. Zero at any position. On off switch. Metric and Inch system to change at any position.

Available on the internet, I used this one:
https://www.3d-electronics.eu/digital-dial-micrometer.html

Printer:

Craftbot Plus

Resolution:

0,2000 mm

Infill:

30%
PLEASE: don't forget to LIKE this design !!!

Just a HOWTO to use this nice tool:

1) level your bed in the way you normally do: with a card or paper.

2) test your printer with a calibration design (you can use this one: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2720578) to see if the bedleveling is ok. Repeat 1 and 2 if not corrected yet.

3) power off your printer and let it cool down totally (or just continue the next day).

4) put your bed and extruderhead to the start position.

5) place the tool on the printer-rods (see photo) and move the tool to every corner and write down the measured distance on a paper. Repeat this a few times to see if they are all the same. If not the same, make them equel by just turning the bed-knobs a little.
Just a fraction is need, because your printer was printing nice already.

6) remove the tool and print the calibration design again, it must be more accurate now.

7) if you are happy with it: keep the final measurement somewhere nearby your printer and tool.

If you need to recalibrate your printer again later, start with (3) and (4), move your bed looking at the micrometer: adjust the knobs until the measured distance in the 4 corners is equal to the distance you have noted on your paper: in just a few minutes your bed will be leveled in the optimal way !!!

I use it when I replace the bed with another one, very handy and no more hassle with calibration cards or papers !!!

--- WIP --- Work In Progress --- Lavori in corso ---

Questo è un progetto di quadricottero ispirato al progetto Firefly Pro, del quale spero di aver migliorato qualche punto che avevo trovato problematico. L'ho chiamato Maticora per la somiglianza col serpente dalla testa rossa
Ha una struttura abbastanza alta per far stare tutta l'elettronica, al momento alloggiato dentro c'è: RX, BEC, Naze32 con i pin verticali, bluetooth sensore celle batterie, buzzer collegato alla Naze e una quantità di cablaggio.
Insieme ho sviluppato anche un micro brandeggio verticale per telecamera FPV.
Le basi superiore e inferiore sono parecchio bucate, questo permette di essere modulari ed eventualmente sviluppare qualche aggancio per attrezzatura supplementare, come per esempio il TX FPV.
Gli ESC vengono alloggiati nella 4 braccia apribili e ventilate (io uso i BL16A della DYS).
La scheda di volo ha 3 posizioni in cui essere ancorata, 1 posteriore, 1 centrale e 1 in posizione avanzata rispetto al centro di spinta.

Il peso del mio quadricottero completo pronto al volo (e batteria da 2200 mAh) è di 628 g circa.

10 cm filo di ferro diametro 1mm

Il progetto è sviluppato con Solid Edge, all'occorrenza invio file sorgente.

description.text: My sound reversing headphone is made to alter our hearing experience and should be worn with two plastic straps—one over your head and one under your chin—and with your eyes closed so that all the focus is on hearing. The ear pieces that are secured on your ears are connected to plastic vacuum cleaner tubes (4cm in diameter and 95cm long) that stretch toward their opposite ends so that what you hear from your left ear actually comes from the right side and vice versa. The sound that you hear from the tube is also altered due to the compression of sound waves inside the narrow tube and some people describe that hearing experience as “being in space” or “a large room where everything sounds distant.” I hope that this headphone will confuse your sense of hearing and give you the experience of being in another place, since we depends so much on our hearing to know our surroundings. By doing so, we will also be "blinded" in a way, since we often use our hearing to “see” what is around us.

title: Surface-mount wall box for one coax F connector and one keystone jack

description.text:
This I made to mount on the wall where the TV is installed. The coax was already clipped along the top of the baseboard. I added an ethernet cable under the baseboard, dremeled a groove up the back side of the baseboard for it, and have both cables going into this box, so now there is a cable outlet and network outlet in one place. It looks a little neater than simply cables hanging off the baseboard.

I got an F barrel coupler on ebay, with the nut and washer included. ( http://www.ebay.com/itm/261672233886 ) That fits into the hex socket on the inside, with the nut and washer on the outside. You can of course get RJ-45 keystone jacks on ebay too.

The cutout for the keystone jack might tend to sag a little, but my Zeus can usually do PLA bridges pretty well. I had to file it slightly afterwards. The design for the keystone receiver is http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:548145 .

I tried to add a honeycomb front surface, to be printed face-down. But I made it too thin, so the slicer omitted it completely, and I got a plain flat front surface. Didn't bother reprinting since it was otherwise OK. So I'm not sure how well that would have worked. You can comment it out if you don't want it (lines 113-114).

This balloon helicopter is a neat toy, tool for teaching basic flight physics, and very nice case study in design and experimentation that could be useful in the undergraduate or high school teaching lab. Notes on flying:
Current best configuration: 16mm blades (blade_16.stl), 13 degree rotor (rotor_13.stl). Short flying video clip located here: http://youtu.be/mo7PvU1rNRc Once printed, insert the three blades into the rotor. Insert the nozzle long ways into a balloon and fill the balloon. Insert the nozzle into the rotor while pinching off the balloon, try to ensure that it is straight. Throw. Try different techniques, I found a little spin can help get it going. It does not perform as well as some of the videos I have seen for commercial versions, possibly simply due to weight (if you have one, post the weight), but hopefully with your help we can improve it together. Notes on making:
[See instructions for full details] All the components should be printable and all you need in addition is a nice balloon. The helicopter was developed using PLA on one MakerBot Replicator 2, but hopefully you can tell me if it works on yours or others. One key element is the need for a very flat build plate since it requires very thin (0.1mm) films to reduce the weight. Notes on design:
I really enjoy design for 3D print and this was a nice case study with interesting constraints. I have included the SolidWorks design files for the latest and greatest version. This has gone through 5 major revisions to date in order to get it to fly as well as it does, but it still needs improvement. To get the weight down, I experimented with various surface profiles, wall thicknesses, geometry, build parameters, etc. My hope is others may try to improve it and we can collectively identify the optimal design. I conducted some basic experiments on variants and have posted STL's for different blades and rotors in case you want to do some of those experiments for yourself. The design files are not well documented but if you have some basic skills with SolidWorks, it should be no problem to figure out.

This design really needs to be made at the highest build quality settings since weight and form are critical. I used 0.1mm layers, 1 shell, 100% fill for the blades and rotor, and switched to 0% fill for the nozzle. All the STL's should already be oriented for best printing. I am also using a glass build plate to ensure a level build platform: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:57411 and taped with green painters tape. Print and assemble 3 blades with the rotor and if necessary run a bead of glue at the joint to the rotor to reduce leaks. It also helps to hold it together and often blades will come flying out (and possibly hit your neighbours kid - I said sorry). In total the printed parts should weight approximately 11g. Notes on the blades:
Carefully peel from build plate with flat plaster knife. There is some technique to develop in getting the blades off without warping the film, you have to experiment. Blade STL file names are appended with the outside width of the outlet opening [start with 12]. Notes on rotors:
Rotor file names are appended with the angle of attack [start with 13]. Notes on nozzle:
Do not glue the nozzle to the rotor; instead insert that into the balloon, with the long part going into the balloon. Although it adds to the weight, this feature is there in order to keep the neck of the balloon from twisting shut when torqued by the blades.

I created these X-Ends to be more accurate with Z. The 8mm Threaded rods will allow this, read more below. These Ends also accept LM8UU Linear bearings for the guide rods. Important: When loading these files into Repetier-Host, I get the message that they are not "Manifold" & may not produce expected results. [Slic3r still slices them] I created these with Sketchup & it says they are fine, as were my prints.

Why use 8mm threads?: ( I plagiarized this next paragraph) It's a very good idea to select layer heights that divide into even numbers of steps of your Z height, having a miss-match of steps as the object builds is going to cause problems - Just to explain this - a 200 step motor using 16x micro-stepping gives you 3200 steps, an M8 threaded rod is 1.25mm per complete revolution so 3200/1.25 = 2560
So 1mm of height (Z) movement takes 2560 motor steps, a layer height of 0.3mm takes 768 motor steps.
If you set a layer height of 0.32, that needs 819.2 steps - not an even number of motor steps, so not ideal.

I can set layer heights @ .01 .02 .03 .04 & get exacting results everytime. I just recently printed a 150mm tall screw with exacting measurements.

title: dovetail grout holder (mini rebar) for corners of tiled walls

description.text: In the bathroom, the walls are covered with ceramic tile. There are a couple of outside corners where special round-nose tiles weren't used; instead they just left a gap, and made the rounded corner by filling with sanded grout. After 35 years the grout tended to crack and fall out from those corners. So, I made these pieces with special settings in skeinforge, to have no shells, only very low-percentage infill, so that they are like trusswork, very porous. I epoxied them to the edges of the tiles, held them in place with masking tape while the epoxy dried, and then ripped off the tape and redid the grout, impregnating it into the plastic trusswork. I don't think it will fall out any more. The plastic is completely covered, so you don't see it after it's done. The dovetailed ends just help to hold them together while they're being glued in place.

Wanting to put my bearings from the original Mendel to good use instead of bushings, I modified the original Aleph Objects X-end clamp to hold a similar bearing configuration as the original Mendel.   • Adjusted spacing of holes so there is 40 mm of spacing in between the smooth and threaded rods instead of 36.
  • Removed one of the straight sideways bearing holes - one is enough
  • Increased angle of angled bearings so the nuts don't collide (new angle is 135 degrees, I think)
  • Reduced height above top holes to save plastic.
    • Uploaded SCAD and STL files are always the latest version.

What would happen if you could only see to your left and right? Up? Down? What about both at the same time? Vision is an amazingly powerful sense, this piece is an effort to explore the effects of altering your vision. These glasses are built like PVC pipes, starting with a pair of glasses that fit onto two tubes, that in turn connect to two 90º angle joints which finally fits onto a second set of tubes.

The effect is that of wearing a periscope over each eye. The viewer can choose to see the world through a combination of up, down, right or left.

This is an optimized version of the i3 build plate with all items set to 0 so no items "float" Also i have made it so that the parts are all upright taking up less space so that it does not take up the entire heatbed. This will print on a 200x200 platform and includes all the printed parts of an i3. The gcode file i have included is to print this in ABS and it is setup for the following settings, Material: ABS
Extrusion Temp: 238c
Filament size: 1.75
Layer Height: .28
Nozzle diameter: .35
Added a z-lift to it so that it prints nicely.
Skin thickness: 4mm
Speeds: loops-90mm/s, solid-120mm/s, sparse-120mm/s,
travel-100mms It takes about 18 hours to print this. I also removed the skirt on this because it would print off the glass. just remember to prime before you print. This is the version found here: http://reprap.org/wiki/Clone_wars:_Prusa_iteraci%C3%B3n_3 I guess it is the box style.
